body:
> On Windows, both cases fail:

I guess this is due to inconsistent behavior of try_lock. Probably best not to rely on this behavior. Maybe we should replace:

```c++
lock = locks.emplace(...).first->second;
if (!lock->try_lock()) {
    return false;
}
```

with something like:

```c++
auto inserted = locks.emplace(...);
if (inserted.second && !inserted.first.second->try_lock()) {
    locks.erase(inserted.first)
    return false;
}
```

